{{more footnotes|date=October 2012}}
'''Istustaya and Papaya''' are two goddesses of destiny with [[Hattians|Hattian]] origin in [[Hittite mythology|Hittite religion]].
The task of Istustaya and Papaya is to spin the thread of life, especially the one of the [[Hittite king|king]]. They sit at the shores of the [[Black Sea]]. After [[Telipinu (god)|Telipinu's]] return they take part on the conference of gods.
== Literature == * [[Volkert Haas]]: ''Die hethitische Literatur'', Walter de Gruyter GmbH & Co. KG, Berlin 2006, pages 111, 322, {{ISBN|978-3-11-018877-6}}
== See also == * [[Moirai|Fates]]
[[Category:Hittite deities]] [[Category:Hittite mythology]] [[Category:Hattian deities]] [[Category:Time and fate goddesses]] [[Category:Textiles in mythology and folklore]]

The "'''Nine Herbs Charm'''" is an [[Anglo-Saxon literature|Old English charm]] recorded in the 10th-century AD<ref name=GORDON92-93>Gordon (1962:92–93).</ref> ''[[Lacnunga]]'' manuscript.<ref name=MACLEODMEES127>Macleod (2006:127).</ref> The charm is intended for the treatment of poisoning and infection by a preparation of nine herbs. The numbers nine and three, [[Numbers in Norse mythology|significant in Germanic paganism]] and later [[Germanic folklore]], are mentioned frequently within the charm.<ref name=MACLEODMEES127/> The poem contains references to [[Christianity|Christian]] and [[Anglo-Saxon paganism|English Pagan]] elements, including a mention of the major [[Germanic paganism|Germanic god]] [[Woden]].
According to [[R. K. Gordon]], the poem is "clearly an old heathen thing which has been subjected to Christian censorship."<ref name=GORDON92-93/> Malcolm Laurence Cameron states that chanting the poem aloud results in a "marvellously incantatory effect".<ref name=CAMERON144>Cameron (1993:144).</ref>
==Poem contents==
===Herbs=== The charm references nine herbs: * ''Mucgƿyrt'' Mugwort (''[[Artemisia vulgaris]]'') * ''Attorlaðe'' (identified as cockspur grass (''[[Echinochloa crus-galli]]'') by R. K. Gordon;<ref name=GORDON92-93/> partially defined by others as betony (''[[Stachys officinalis]]'')<ref>[http://home.comcast.net/~modean52/oeme_dictionaries.htm OEME Dictionary]</ref>) * ''Stune'' Lamb's cress (''[[Cardamine hirsuta]]'') * ''Ƿegbrade'' Plantain (''[[Plantago]]'') *''Mægðe'' Mayweed (''[[Matricaria]]'') * ''Stiðe'' Nettle (''[[Urtica]]'') * ''Ƿergulu'' Crab-apple (''[[Malus]]'') * ''Fille'' Thyme ([[Thymus vulgaris]])<ref name=GORDON92-93/> *''Finule'' Fennel (''[[Foeniculum vulgare]]'')
At the end of the charm, prose instructions are given to take the above-mentioned herbs, crush them to dust, and to mix them with old [[soap]] and [[apple juice]]. Further instructions are given to make a paste from water and ashes, boil fennel into the paste, bathe it with beaten egg&nbsp;– both before and after the prepared salve is applied.
Further, the charm directs the reader to sing the charm three times over each of the herbs as well as the apple before they are prepared, into the mouth of the wounded, both of their ears, and over the wound itself prior to the application of the salve.
===Woden=== The poem contains one of two Old English mentions of ''[[Odin|Woden]]'' in Old English poetry; the other is ''[[Maxims (Old English poems)|Maxims I]]'' of the ''[[Exeter Book]]''. The paragraph reads as follows: {{bq|text=<poem>A snake came crawling, it bit a man. Then Woden took nine glory-twigs, Smote the serpent so that it flew into nine parts. There apple brought this pass against poison, That she nevermore would enter her house.<ref name=GORDON92-93/></poem>}}
Suggestions have been made that this passage describes Woden coming to the assistance of the herbs through his use of nine twigs, each twig inscribed with the [[rune|runic]] first-letter initial of a plant.<ref name=MAYR-HARTING27>Mayr-Harting (1991:27).</ref>
==See also== *[[Galdr]] *''[[Hávamál]]'' *[[Mímir]] *[[Merseburg Incantations]]
